text.tspan: BIO-DEBUGGER

g.text: Access-First Protocol for Technical Overwhelm • Educational (not medical advice) • Use what helps; skip what doesn’t

text.tspan: GREEN (1): I can think clearly. I’m learning.
YELLOW (2): I’m strained; I can continue only if I simplify.
RED (3): I’m flooded (panic/anger/shutdown/tears/urge to quit)
Pause → Step back → Observe (body + urge) → Prepare to proceed with a deliberate action.
Inhale 2–3 sec → Exhale 6–8 sec × 5 rounds.
Name 5 things you see → feel feet/hands → turn your head slowly and re-locate yourself in the room.

tspan.tspan: If you’re still RED after 2 rounds: STOP RULES (Block 5). Do not continue.

text.tspan: 3) YELLOW TRACK — REDUCE LOAD
☐ Close extra tabs/windows (leave only what you’re using).
☐ Turn off notifications / mute chat for 10 minutes.
☐ Reduce sensory intensity (brightness/audio).
☐ Write the goal in one sentence: “I am trying to ____.”
☐ Make the next step “tiny” (Block 4), maybe research one thing.
☐ Set a timer: 5 minutes (then reassess state).
☐ Reproduce once (same steps, observe exactly what happens and collect info/errors).
☐ Single-variable change (research and change ONE thing → test once).
☐ Return to known-good (revert preset/file/version/settings).
Stop and switch strategies if any are true:
☐ I’ve made 3 changes without understanding cause/effect.
☐ I’m repeating the same steps and learning nothing new.
☐ My body alarm is high (shaking, nausea, tunnel vision, shutdown).
☐ I’m arguing with myself / self-attacking / “I’m broken” thoughts.
Switch to (choose ONE):
☐ 5-minute break + water + return to Block 1
☐ Park it: write “next step” and stop for today
Stopping is a skill. Pausing protects future progress.
